<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: LOMITA; SHERIFF OPENS 
OMBUDSMAN OFFICE TO FIELD COMPLAINTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 An ombudsman's office has opened in Lomita, part of a long-anticipated effort 
to soothe community anger over the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department's 
past use-of-force policies. Five retired judges were appointed to review 
complaints forwarded by the ombudsman's office and to provide an independent 
review in cases involving allegedly excessive use of force. 
</P>
<P>
 Rudolph De Leon, 69, a retired police captain who worked as a special 
assistant to former California Atty. Gen. John Van de Kamp, was hired in 
mid-March for the ombudsman's job. He began work Monday as the Sheriff 
Department's in-house investigator of citizen complaints.  
</P>
<P>
 De Leon, the unanimous choice of the Board of Supervisors for the $60,200- 
a-year job, vowed to provide swift and efficient response to community concerns 
and complaints.  
</P>
<P>
 "I want to give people confidence that their complaints are going to be 
addressed, and there will be fairness and efficiency in dealing with their 
complaints to their satisfaction," he said. 
</P>
