<HEADLINE>
<P>
ON BEING A SINGLE PARENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BETTIJANE LEVINE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Shoshana Alexander, author of "In Praise of Single Parents," offers these 
tips:  
</P>
<P>
 * Take on the job as if you were about to climb a mountain. Dedicate yourself 
to the task.In other words, choose to do it, instead of trying to find ways out 
of it -- such as looking for a partner to share the parenting. Being a single 
parent will strengthen you as a person. 
</P>
<P>
 * Make the child a priority. Choose work that has flexible hours, if possible. 
Create a schedule that includes daily time with the child. Lead a 
child-oriented life, but not a child-centered life. 
</P>
<P>
 * Extend your family. It is crucial to include others in your and your child's 
lives. Reach out to friends, neighbors, relatives. Join support groups or live 
with others. Do whatever you can to build a group of people you consider to be 
family but who are not necessarily blood relations. Remember the South African 
adage: "It takes a whole village to raise a child." 
</P>
<P>
 * Learn that it's OK to ask for help. In fact, it's essential. Realize that 
the friend or extended family member you ask for assistance may consider it a 
gift and an honor to be asked, whereas you consider it a favor. BETTIJANE 
LEVINE 
</P>
</TEXT>
