<HEADLINE>
<P>
DINING WITHOUT WHINING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KATHLEEN O. RYAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A few tips from parents for avoiding mealtime meltdowns: 
</P>
<P>
 * Look for restaurants that cater to families. 
</P>
<P>
 * Go during off hours to avoid a wait, or make reservations. 
</P>
<P>
 * Order the check with the meal so there won't be an additional wait to leave. 
</P>
<P>
 * Take restless children for a walk. 
</P>
<P>
 * Bring crayons and paper or a small quiet toy. 
</P>
<P>
 * Bring a small snack or ask for crackers before the meal. 
</P>
<P>
 * Order appetizers or finger foods for toddlers. 
</P>
<P>
 * Bring your own toddler-sized utensils and cups for little ones. 
</P>
<P>
 * Ask for foam cups with lids for drinks. 
</P>
<P>
 * Always ask for extra napkins. 
</P>
<P>
 * Include your child in the dining experience. 
</P>
<P>
 * Don't allow children to run around or disturb other customers. 
</P>
<P>
 * Discipline children away from the dining room. 
</P>
<P>
 * Reward good behavior. KATHLEEN O. RYAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Sidebar 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA051894-0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 042860 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
