<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: IRVINE; ADDING HER OWN PAGE TO THE STORY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHELBY GRAD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Kris Rideout's fascination with Asia dates to her childhood, when her father 
would return home from business trips filled with stories about the region. 
</P>
<P>
 So it didn't surprise friends and family members when Rideout, who grew up in 
Irvine and graduated from University High School in 1991, majored in Asian 
Pacific Studies at Loyola Marymount University in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 Her continuing interest in the Far East landed Rideout a 1994 Fulbright 
scholarship. She will travel to Singapore this summer to study Asian woman 
entrepreneurs. 
</P>
<P>
 Rideout, 21, said the scholarship will allow her to research the impact that 
female entrepreneurs have on the Pacific Rim economy and culture. 
</P>
<P>
 "The role that women are playing in Asia and around the world is very 
important," she said. "It's the kind of thing that is hard to learn from books 
without going there and meeting the people." 
</P>
<P>
 Rideout will leave Orange County for Singapore in July. She will begin an MBA 
program at a university there and interview dozens of businesswomen in the 
region. 
</P>
<P>
 At the end of her year abroad, Rideout will write a report that looks at what 
Asian businesswomen are doing and compares their status to women in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
 Rideout was born in New York but has lived in Irvine since she was 12. Her 
father worked at IBM and traveled frequently to Asia. "His stories fascinated 
me," she said. "I was very interested in the Pacific Rim, even as a child." 
</P>
<P>
 Rideout said she hopes to learn Japanese when she returns to the United 
States. She also plans to earn a business administration degree from a U.S. 
university. Eventually, she'd like to work in international business. 
</P>
<P>
 The Fulbright Scholarship program was named after the late U.S. Sen. William 
Fulbright of Arkansas. It is administered by the federal government. Considered 
one of academia's most prestigious fellowships, the program is designed to 
foster understanding between the United States and foreign countries. SHELBY 
GRAD 
</P>
</TEXT>
