<HEADLINE>
<P>
BID TO SAVE TWO MEN'S PROGRAMS AT UCLA TURNED DOWN BY COURT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By WENDY WITHERSPOON, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Superior Judge Alan Haber in Santa Monica denied an application for a 
preliminary injunction against UCLA that would have forced the school to 
reinstate its men's swimming and men's gymnastics programs. 
</P>
<P>
 UCLA said last August that it would drop men's swimming and men's and women's 
gymnastics after the 1993-94 academic year, but reinstated women's gymnastics 
two weeks later when threatened with a gender-equity lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
 Members of the men's swimming and men's gymnastics teams were awarded a 
temporary restraining order on April 18 preventing the school from cutting the 
programs, but Tuesday's decision allows UCLA to proceed with their elimination. 
</P>
<P>
 Ivan W. Halperin, the attorney representing the male swimmers and gymnasts, 
said he has not determined whether he will appeal the decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA051894-0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 042893 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
